        <TD bgcolor='black' valign='top'><font color='white' face='Verdana' size='2'> Am I the only one thinking that the "Level Cap" on the items is good?</P><P>Yes, maybe it's easier for melees to get haste items they can use, but with that level cap it's more fit that you can 'outgrow' an item.<BR>As for Focus III only droping from raid encounters, I didn't see anyone complaining that Flowing Thougt Items are not droped by orc pawns and I find Focus items MUCH more usefull than FT.</P><P>The only thing that kinda bothers me is that there is no Affliction Damage bonus, i.e. Your dot will do 20% more damage in the same time.<BR>One problem with Necromancers is that we can't do quick damage, which is required in most exp groups (A DoT that does 2000dmg in 90 seconds isn't any good if the mob dies in 40 seconds). What the focus items did for us, is that we can now keep our damage output up for a longer amount of time, since they cost less mana and stay on longer, but our actual DPS didn't increase.<BR>If you look at Wizards, they got Improved Damage which increases their DPS effectively by 20%, if you add Spell Haste you can argue that it increases their DPS as well, and Mana Preservation helps them to keep the damage up for a longer period of time.<BR>Same with Healers and Improved Healing. They now can heal more damage in less time.</P><P>We <u>need</u> a Improved Affliction focus that either increases the total dot damage (same ticks, more damage), or reduces the time for the dot to do it's full damage (less ticks, same damage) to be competitive and attractive for groups.<BR>Also, a Casting Subtlety Focus, like the Arch Skill, would be nice to have, since the agro issue with dots is still unbalanced as compared to other forms of damage.</P><P> </font></td>
      </tr>
      <TR>
        <TD bgcolor='black' valign='top'
 nowrap><b><font color='white' face='Verdana' size='2'>Tenaiya</font></b></td>
        <TD bgcolor='black' valign='top'><font color='white' face='Verdana' size='2'> I'm not quite ready to bash VI over this yet, but they do deserve a little /bonk.</P><P>Increasing the dmg percentage would truly have been a better way of implementing the focus items. At the very least, even the most crappily equipped level 50 caster would be able to squeeze some benefit out of existing gear.</P><P>Hopefully today's changed list will at least make some focus assignments seem more sensible. But I'm more than likely to see the few meager items that I have with level III effects downgraded to level II since all the level III items seem rather high end. Oh well, small boost for dooming darkness and the occasional IB at least I guess.</P><P>I think it would be a good idea if they put focus effects on all class-specific quested armour that don't already have effects on them. Velious armour, obviously, but also the Twilight Sea and Temple of Sol quests.</P><P>Tenaiya Soulscorcher</font></td>
      </tr>
      <TR>
        <TD bgcolor='black' valign='top'
 nowrap><b><font color='white' face='Verdana' size='2'>Briljin</font></b></td>
        <TD bgcolor='black' valign='top'><font color='white' face='Verdana' size='2'> Yes the focus items where poorily implemented and thought out.  There should be no spell level range for the effects, they should work with ALL spells (just like Haste items do) and it should be a constant value instead of a random value.</P><P>An A for effort but a D for implementation...</P><P>Bril</P><P> </font></td>
      </tr>
      <TR>
        <TD bgcolor='black' valign='top'
 nowrap><b><font color='white' face='Verdana' size='2'>Tenaiya</font></b></td>
        <TD bgcolor='black' valign='top'><font color='white' face='Verdana' size='2'> It's true that Focus items are probably more useful than FT. The problem is that putting level III effects only on uber-level encounters means that they are effectively limiting a set of very useful items to a very small subset of people. As the FT items aren't quite as useful, limiting them to a very small subset of people matters less.</P><P>To add to the problem, people who are levelling up now will, after level 49, suddenly find their effectiveness reduced after having had 40+ levels with focus items. The jump in casting times will become a lot bigger because apart from the longer casting time of higher level spells, you have to add the 33% that was shaved off the under-44 DoT. Also, at level 50, Ignite Bones would do 600 dmg with damage enhancement, while Indisious Retrogression does 550.</P><P>While it makes more sense that you outgrow items, there is currently no clear way how you can outgrow items in a logical progression. All we can see is a huge leap in difficulty between obtaining level II and level III items, with most level III items obtainable only by large guilds. Meaning that you have to be practically level 60 before you can get these items. And 12 levels (10 of which are hell levels) where you can't get any generically useful focus items. </P><P>Taking the FBSS for example, it doesn't stop working for melees when they hit level 50 and even if it did, they have things to replace it before they're 60. Whereas we don't in the current state of affairs.</P><P>Melees also get the choice to carry on using their haste items, even if it totally sucks for their level. Plenty of level 50+ tanks still use FBSS. With the level limit, casters don't have this luxury. The decision is taken out of our hands.</P><P>If they do intend to keep this level based thing, there *must* be a more gradual difficulty in obtaining these effects. Not the big chasm we see at the moment. There need to be level III items which can be obtained by level 50-ish.</P><P>Tenaiya Soulscorcher</font></td>
      </tr>
      <TR>
        <TD bgcolor='black' valign='top'
 nowrap><b><font color='white' face='Verdana' size='2'>Dinomight</font></b></td>
        <TD bgcolor='black' valign='top'><font color='white' face='Verdana' size='2'> One of the better arguements I read yesterday, think on the wiz board, was why at 19th level can I save regents every cast, nuke harder, and dot longer, but come 24th and new spells (thus, it would follow, more skill/better effects), I actually do less? </P><P>I learned how to ride a bike at 3.  When I turned 15 and learned how to drive a car I wasn't unable to ride the bike still.</P><P><i><b><font color=gold><font size=4>Dinomight Questaholic</b></font id=size4><BR>Master of the Lizard Dance on Test  {The Grove}</i></font id=gold></font></td>
